      "title": "Established trauma systems -Queensland Trauma Registry",
      "abstract": "XFM scanning was performed using the Maia detector developed by CSIRO. Raster scanning of emitted X-ray fluorescence was performed over the full sample area in the silicon frame (4 mm × 4 mm) with a pixel size of 1.25 × 1.25. Data processing included spectral deconvolution, background subtraction and projection of separated images into elemental spectral profiles. Results: Each of the trace metals, Fe, Cu and Zn, were distributed in distinct layers of the hippocampus; Zn was expressed in the hilus extending from the dentate gyrus to the CA3, tracking the mossy fibres of the trisynaptic pathway. The levels of Zn in the hilar region of the CA3 (28.89 ± 1.30 ppm) were high compared to the molecular layer of the dentate gyrus (9.77 ± 1.55 ppm) and in the CA3 region where a high level of mossy fibre synaptic connections are present (22.4 ± 0.75 ppm). Preliminary data indicates an increase in Zn in the hilus in the TBI group. Cu could be discerned at the cellular level in discrete foci associated with hilar neurons. Cellular association was confirmed by co-registration after thionin staining of neurons. Conclusions: This study demonstrates that synchrotron-XFM can be used to accurately assess changes in trace metal element content and distribution in brain tissue slices to investigate TBI and other neurodegenerative diseases. Acknowledgements: We wish to acknowledge the support of the Victorian Neurotrauma Initiative through the Victorian Transport Accident Commission. Part of this work was undertaken on the Microspectroscopy Beamline at the Australian Synchrotron, Victoria, Australia."
